One approach to this problem has been to place a lower bound on the mass of the inner DM halo by constructing a “maximum disk” model to fit the rotation curve (Kalnajs 1983; van Albada & Sancisi 1986). Such a model attributes the highest possible mass-to-light ratio (
/ M L
) to the luminous matter, usually consistent with a non-hollow DM halo. There are a number of indirect dynamical arguments suggesting that the disk mass is in fact close to maximum for most bright galaxies (e.g. van Albada & Sancisi 1986; Freeman 1992; Debattista & Sellwood 1998) or nearly so (Athanassoula, Bosma & Papaioannou 1987; Bosma 1999). Counter-arguments against maximum disks have been advanced by Efstathiou, Lake, & Negroponte (1982), Bahcall & Casertano (1985), Bottema (1993, 1997), van der Kruit (1995), Courteau & Rix (1999) and others. Several recent studies, motivated by cosmological structure formation simulations, have addressed dark halo structure and the relation between dark halo size and galaxy size (e.g. Navarro et al. 1996, Syer & White 1998, Syer, Mao, & Mo 1999) and have generally favored strongly sub-maximal disk models.
